{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b The playbook these all share:}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Open source / source-available is the marketing, not the product.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab They DO operate their own managed hosting \u8212- but they have full-time SREs to do it. {\b You don't.} For VBWD the equivalent is distribution via existing self-host marketplaces (Cloudron, Elest.io, Coolify) that capture the hosting revenue without you running ops.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Founder writes; no founder-led sales calls.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Single hero comparison ("X vs Calendly" / "X vs Google Analytics").\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Pricing on the page, no "contact us."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 6.\tx360\tab Documentation is the product surface.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Conclusion:} VBWD's first 12 months should imitate the Plausible/Cal.com/Ghost playbook with a Marc Lou-style one-time license SKU as the launch lever. Skip the GoHighLevel-killer pitch until Y2.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
